President Trump and his administration met with South Korean President Moon Jae-in to discuss North Korea and trade. They have a strong plan for dealing with North Korea, and they want to negotiate a fair trade deal with South Korea. Secretary of Commerce Wilbur Ross highlighted the trade imbalance with South Korea, particularly in the automotive industry, and the non-tariff trade barriers faced by US companies. Gary Cohn also mentioned the trade deficit with China and the predatory practices they engage in. President Trump emphasized the need to reduce trade deficits with many countries, including South Korea, and praised South Korea for their military purchases from the US and their interest in purchasing natural gas. President Moon's remarks were not provided with a translation.